                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">It took 15 calls and ranting and raving to talk to a supervisor, but it got the job done.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />That's too much work for what should have been done anyhow. :/<br />Stories like this are all too common, friend of mine lost a fungi and all his droppable gear to his guildmate who was his "friend" atleast they put in the shared bank thing finally. I have found 2 things when dealing with GM's (not guides most guides while possibly cool people generally suck and are jerks) anyhow every time i had to talk to a gm i was #1 straight forward (not pushy or excited) #2 wasn't doing something else like pulling mobs or whatever I gave them the time to explain the situation. I also added most everytime that I understood their abilities are VERY limited as to what they are allowed to do and any help would be great. I never kissed ass or got crazy threatening to quit or calling them names and after atleast 30 petitions of real problems ie lost item/body under the world and such I haven't been let down yet. Perhaps I am lucky but I think handling them in the way you want to be handled is the best approach and explaining you understand their limitations is key. Honestly i think that kinda gets them wanting to help you since they feel worthless because you don't expect them to help because they can't lol.<br />Lune<br /></span id="msg"></font></td>
